explanation:
Explain why each symbol is required for unreachable-code (MISRA) analysis:

- struct MHD_RqDAuth
  Required because parse_dauth_params takes a pointer to this structure and writes into many of its members (nonce, opaque, response, username, username_ext, realm, uri, qop_raw, cnonce, nc, userhash, algo3, qop). Knowing the exact declaration (member names and types) is necessary to tell whether any writes or subsequent reads are ill-formed or conditionally unusable, and to determine whether some assignments or branches are impossible (e.g. if a member type or accessor had side effects or constraints).

- struct MHD_RqDAuthParam
  The function manipulates MHD_RqDAuthParam instances (local and those pointing into pdauth). The structure layout (fields value.str, value.len and quoted) is used to set values and later test userhash. To reason about whether code paths that set these fields can be reached or are redundant/unreachable, the exact fields and semantics are required.

- struct _MHD_cstr_w_len
  parse_dauth_params builds the tk_names array from instances of this type and relies on its members (str and len) for all token matching logic. The token-matching branches and loops that drive reachability depend on the values and semantics of these fields.

- _MHD_S_STR_W_LEN (macro)
  This macro constructs the static token constants (nonce_tk, opaque_tk, etc.). Its expansion defines the token strings and lengths; to determine if certain token-comparison branches can ever be taken (and thus whether code guarded by those branches is reachable), you must know what strings/lengths are produced.

- MHD_str_equal_caseless_bin_n_
  Used for caseless binary comparison in token matching. The result of this function controls whether the inner parameter-parsing branch is entered. For unreachable-code analysis you must know its semantics (return values, side effects if any) to decide if a branch can ever be true or always false.

- MHD_str_equal_caseless_quoted_s_bin_n
  Used to compare a quoted userhash value with "true". Determining whether the assignment pdauth->userhash = ... can be taken (and whether alternate branches are reachable) depends on this function's semantics.

- MHD_str_equal_caseless_s_bin_n_
  Used to compare an unquoted userhash value with "true". Same reasoning as above: its behaviour affects whether the assignment and subsequent code are reachable.

- get_rq_dauth_algo
  Called at the end and its result is stored into pdauth->algo3. If this function never returns (e.g., aborts, longjmp, or traps) or has constrained return values that make subsequent code unreachable, that directly affects reachability of the function's final return and any code after the call. For MISRA unreachable-code analysis we must know whether this call is a normal terminating call.

- get_rq_dauth_qop
  Same rationale as get_rq_dauth_algo: its behavior determines reachability of the final return and whether code paths after its call are reachable.

- mhd_assert (macro/function)
  The function uses mhd_assert in many places. Depending on its definition it may expand to nothing (no effect) or to code that aborts/longjmps on failure. To determine whether code immediately following an assertion is reachable you must know the implementation and whether any assertion could unconditionally abort or otherwise make code unreachable.

- memset
  The function uses memset to zero local structures. While memset itself does not affect control flow, knowing it is standard and has no unusual side-effects is necessary to exclude it from causing unreachable-code issues; listing it ensures the analyzer confirms it as a normal call.

- bool / true / false (stdbool)
  The function relies on boolean type and literal values (assignments to pdauth->userhash, returns). The exact definitions ensure assignments and comparisons are well-formed and do not introduce unexpected control-flow behavior.

Notes: The above symbols cover all types, macros and callees that influence the conditional logic and assertions inside parse_dauth_params. For a MISRA C unreachable-code determination you must know the precise semantics (return behavior, side effects, and expansions) of the listed symbols so you can decide whether each conditional/loop/return can actually be reached during execution.
